# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#Topic Canvas_State

Canvas maintains a stack of state that allows hierarchical drawing, commonly used
to implement windows and views. The initial state has an identity matrix and and an infinite clip.
Even with a wide-open clip, drawing is constrained by the bounds of the
Canvas Surface or Device.

Canvas_State contains a Canvas_Clip, Canvas_Matrix, and Draw_Filter.
Canvas_Clip describes the area that may be drawn to.
Canvas_Matrix transforms the geometry.
Draw_Filter (deprecated on most platforms) modifies the paint before drawing.

save(), saveLayer, saveLayerPreserveLCDTextRequests, and saveLayerAlpha
save Canvas_State and return the depth of the stack.

restore() and restoreToCount revert Canvas_State to its value when saved.

Each Canvas_State on the stack intersects Canvas_Clip with the previous Canvas_Clip,
and concatenates Canvas_Matrix with the previous Canvas_Matrix.
The intersected Canvas_Clip makes the drawing area the same or smaller;
the concatenated Canvas_Matrix may move the origin and potentially scale or rotate
the coordinate space.

Canvas does not require balancing the Canvas_State stack but it is a good idea
to do so. Calling save() without restore() will eventually cause Skia to fail;
mismatched save() and restore() create hard to find bugs.

It is not possible to use Canvas_State to draw outside of the clip defined by the
previous Canvas_State.

#Example
#Description
Draw to ever smaller clips; then restore drawing to full canvas.
Note that the second clipRect is not permitted to enlarge Canvas_Clip.
##
void draw(SkCanvas* canvas) {
    SkPaint paint;
    canvas->clear(SK_ColorWHITE);               // draws to entire destination
    canvas->save();                             // records stack depth to restore  
    canvas->clipRect(SkRect::MakeWH(100, 100)); // constrains drawing to clip
    canvas->clear(SK_ColorRED);                 // draws to limit of clip
    canvas->save();                             // records stack depth to restore 
    canvas->clipRect(SkRect::MakeWH(50, 150));  // Rect below 100 is ignored
    canvas->clear(SK_ColorBLUE);                // draws to smaller clip
    canvas->restore();                          // enlarges clip
    canvas->drawLine(20, 20, 150, 150, paint);  // line below 100 is not drawn
    canvas->restore();                          // enlarges clip
    canvas->drawLine(150, 20, 50, 120, paint);  // line below 100 is drawn
}
## 

Each Canvas_Clip uses the current Canvas_Matrix for its coordinates.

#Example
void draw(SkCanvas* canvas) {
    canvas->clipRect(SkRect::MakeWH(100, 100));
    canvas->clear(SK_ColorRED);
    canvas->scale(.5, .5);
    canvas->clipRect(SkRect::MakeWH(100, 100));
    canvas->clear(SK_ColorBLUE);
}
##

#SeeAlso save() saveLayer saveLayerPreserveLCDTextRequests saveLayerAlpha restore() restoreToCount

#Method int save()

Saves Canvas_Matrix, Canvas_Clip, and Draw_Filter (Draw_Filter deprecated on most platforms).
Calling restore() discards changes to Canvas_Matrix, Canvas_Clip, and Draw_Filter,
restoring the Canvas_Matrix, Canvas_Clip, and Draw_Filter to their state when save() was called.

Canvas_Matrix may be changed by translate(), scale(), rotate(), skew(), concat(), setMatrix, and resetMatrix.
Canvas_Clip may be changed by clipRect, clipRRect, clipPath, clipRegion.
Draw_Filter may be changed by setDrawFilter.

Saved Canvas state is put on a stack; multiple calls to save() should be balance by an equal number of
calls to restore().

Call restoreToCount with result to restore this and subsequent saves.

#Return Depth of saved stack. ##

#Example
void draw(SkCanvas* canvas) {
    SkPaint paint;
    SkRect rect = { 0, 0, 25, 25 };
    canvas->drawRect(rect, paint);
    canvas->save();
    canvas->translate(50, 50);
    canvas->drawRect(rect, paint);
    canvas->restore();
    paint.setColor(SK_ColorRED);
    canvas->drawRect(rect, paint);
}
##

